[4] Cholera - Sudan (South)
Date: Tue, 7 Nov 2006
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: Sudan Tribune [edited]
http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article18529

A total of 200 cases of acute watery diarrhea have been admitted to
Juba hospital since last week, according to an internal UNMIS note
warring international staff in the region to take the necessary
hygienic measures.
Another acute watery diarrhea outbreak is believed to be cholera in
the capital of southern Sudan, Juba. It is believed to have started
at Munuki but has rapidly spread to almost all corners of Juba, a UN
source said.
Cholera outbreak has killed at least 424 people and sickened 14 000
since January 2006 in southern Sudan, and officials are concerned the
disease could spread to other countries.
Cholera has broken out in most states of Sudan, including North and
South Darfur, but the toll does not include West Darfur where
agencies have little access due to insecurity.
The first suspected cases were reported at the end of January in Yei.
The disease was then reported in Juba, the capital of southern Sudan,
and it has spread quickly. Juba has a population of more than 250 000
people who are known to rely heavily on polluted water from the River
Nile.
--
Brent Barrett
Indianapolis, IN
<salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
[ProMED thanks Mr. Barrett for this post. Juba can be found in the
state of Bahr al Jebel in south Sudan at:
