[7] Cholera, IDPs - Uganda (Pader)
Date: Mon, 6 Nov 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Daily Monitor (Uganda) [edited]
<http://www.monitor.co.ug/news/news110617.php>

Four internally displaced persons (IDPs) have so far died of cholera
in Pader district. The disease broke out in the area 2 weeks ago
after a lull of about 6 months.
Pader residents say the 1st victim was a woman who had been attending
to a patient at Kitgum Hospital. She reportedly returned home at Tyer
IDP camp after contracting the disease and died after a few days.
"We discovered late that she was suffering from cholera. Then she
died mysteriously," said a resident at Tyer, who confirmed that 2
deaths had so far been registered at the camp.
The Pader district LC5 Chairman, Mr Peter Odok, told Daily Monitor on
Wed, 1 Nov 2006, that the disease had spread to Pajule IDP camp and
Pader town council, which have so far registered one death each. He
said 4 people had so far died while 22 were suffering from the
disease in 3 different camps. "The health situation here needs
immediate intervention because the rate at which the disease is
spreading is alarming. We fear that should there be no proper
measures to control it, many people might die," Odok said.
[Byline: Colombus Ono]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The Pader district is in northern Uganda and can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/uganda.pdf>. -
