[8] Cholera - Guinea
Date: Fri, 3 Nov 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: IRIN [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/5038f7b91d203a973bc1aba656c347f6.htm>

Cholera has surged again in Guinea since the rainy season began in
June 2006, including in the capital, Conakry, where the Health
Ministry reported 626 cases so far this year.
"The latest wave is occurring because of poor sanitation during the
main rainy season and a lack of potable water," said Emmanuel Roland
Malano, who head's the government's division of epidemiological
diseases. He said 25 people have died in Conakry, including 19 who
passed away at their homes.
In the remote Forest Region in the southeast, 13 people died of
cholera in Sep 2006 in the town of Kissidougou and another 20 died in
the town of Lola, according to Mory Moussa Doukoure, a doctor at the
laboratory in Conakry's Donka Hospital, Guinea's main health facility.
In 2005, Guinea had 1956 cases of cholera between mid-Jul and early
September 2005 with 72 deaths, according to the WHO.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of the country of Guinea can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/guinea.pdf>. The
Forest region (Guinee Forestiere) is located inland in the extreme
southeastern area while the capital Conakry is located in Guinee
Maritime on the western Atlantic coast. - Mod.LL]
