[12] Shigellosis - USA (Wyoming)
Date: Tue, 7 Nov 2006
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: Billings (Montana) Gazette [edited]
<http://www.billingsgazette.net/articles/2006/11/07/news/wyoming/78-bacteria.txt>

At least 17 people in Fremont County, most of them on the Wind River
Indian Reservation, have come down with shigellosis, a
gastrointestinal infection caused by bacteria.
"It doesn't appear that there's any large common source of food or
water" causing the infections, said Dr. Tracy Murphy, the Wyoming
state epidemiologist. "It's being spread now through one infected
person through another."
Murphy said anyone who thinks they might be infected should avoid
going to school or work and should see a doctor. "Certainly, if they
have a gastrointestinal illness that could be shigella, we want them
to see a health care provider for their own health benefit and to
help us get a handle on controlling it," he said.
Wyoming has had 5 to 8 outbreaks of the disease in the past 5 years.
Murphy said the best way to defend against the bacteria is to
thoroughly wash your hands after using the bathroom or coming into
contact with fecal matter.
--
Brent Barrett
Indianapolis, IN
<salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
